BTD_model_data <- fread("/Users/wanrug/Documents/BTD_model_data.csv")
#BTD_model_data$treatment_duration_group <- factor(BTD_model_data$treatment_duration_group)
BTD_model_data$SVI_3digit_class <- factor(BTD_model_data$SVI_3digit_class)
BTD_model_data$group_BP <- factor(BTD_model_data$group_BP)
BTD_model_data$group_MHAndSU <- factor(BTD_model_data$group_MHAndSU)
#Check variable names 
BTD_model_data$der_sex <- factor(BTD_model_data$der_sex)
###BTD_model_data$age <- factor(BTD_model_data$age) #if age is a categorical; if not, ignore this
 

#BTD_model_data$treatment_duration_group <- relevel(BTD_model_data$treatment_duration_group, ref = "0-3 months")
BTD_model_data$SVI_3digit_class <- relevel(BTD_model_data$SVI_3digit_class, ref = "High")
BTD_model_data$group_BP <- relevel(BTD_model_data$group_BP, ref = "Low-provider density")
BTD_model_data$group_MHAndSU <- relevel(BTD_model_data$group_MHAndSU, ref = "Low mental health services density")
BTD_model_data$der_sex <- relevel(BTD_model_data$der_sex, ref = "M") #To put male as reference 
BTD_model_data<-as.data.frame(BTD_model_data)
# Ensure pay_type is a factor
BTD_model_data$pay_type <- as.factor(BTD_model_data$pay_type)

# Relevel the factor to set "Commercial" as the reference level
BTD_model_data$pay_type <- relevel(BTD_model_data$pay_type, ref = "Commercial")

BTD_model_data$alcohol <- as.factor(BTD_model_data$alcohol)
BTD_model_data$nodrug <- as.factor(BTD_model_data$nodrug)
BTD_model_data$schizo <- as.factor(BTD_model_data$schizo)
BTD_model_data$bipolar <- as.factor(BTD_model_data$bipolar)
BTD_model_data$anxiety <- as.factor(BTD_model_data$anxiety)
BTD_model_data$ptsd <- as.factor(BTD_model_data$ptsd)
BTD_model_data$hiv <- as.factor(BTD_model_data$hiv)
BTD_model_data$depression <- as.factor(BTD_model_data$depression)
BTD_model_data$outpatient <- as.factor(BTD_model_data$outpatient)
# Convert specified columns to factors
columns_to_convert <- c("psychiatric", "telehealth", "mat", "induction", "bupre_tx", "pdc_90")
BTD_model_data[columns_to_convert] <- lapply(BTD_model_data[columns_to_convert], as.factor) 
# Define time and censoring indicator
BTD_model_data <- BTD_model_data %>%
  mutate(
    time = pmin(episode.duration, 180),    # Censor at 180 days
    status = ifelse(episode.duration < 180, 1, 0)  # 1 = discontinued, 0 = censored
  )

# Load the required package
library(survival)

# Fit the Cox proportional hazards model
cox_model <- coxph(Surv(time, status) ~ der_sex+SVI_3digit_class+group_BP+group_MHAndSU+pat_region+age_at_episode+dayssup+pay_type, data = BTD_model_data)

# Summary of the Cox model
summary(cox_model)

Kaplan Meier survival curves

KM curve on SVI

# Load required libraries
library(survival)
library(survminer)
## Warning: package 'survminer' was built under R version 4.3.3
## Loading required package: ggplot2
## Loading required package: ggpubr
## 
## Attaching package: 'survminer'
## The following object is masked from 'package:survival':
## 
##     myeloma
# Prepare the survival object
surv_obj <- Surv(BTD_model_data$time, BTD_model_data$status)

# Fit a Kaplan-Meier survival curve stratified by SVI_3digit_class
km_fit <- survfit(surv_obj ~ SVI_3digit_class, data = BTD_model_data)

# Plot the Kaplan-Meier curves
ggsurvplot(
  km_fit, 
  data = BTD_model_data,
  pval = TRUE,                      # Show p-value for log-rank test
  conf.int = TRUE,                  # Show confidence intervals
  xlab = "Days",                    # Label for x-axis
  ylab = "Probability of Retension",    # Label for y-axis
  legend.title = "SVI by 3-digit ZIP", # Title for the legend
  legend.labs = levels(as.factor(BTD_model_data$SVI_3digit_class)), # Labels for the legend
#  risk.table = TRUE,                # Add risk table below the plot
  ggtheme = theme_minimal()         # Apply a clean theme
)

# Load required libraries
library(survival)
library(survminer)

# Prepare the survival object
surv_obj <- Surv(BTD_model_data$time, BTD_model_data$status)

# Fit a Kaplan-Meier survival curve stratified by SVI_3digit_class
km_fit <- survfit(surv_obj ~ SVI_3digit_class, data = BTD_model_data)

# Plot the Kaplan-Meier curves
ggsurvplot(
  km_fit, 
  data = BTD_model_data,
  pval = TRUE,                      # Show p-value for log-rank test
  conf.int = TRUE,                  # Show confidence intervals
  xlab = "Days",                    # Label for x-axis
  ylab = "Probability of Retension",    # Label for y-axis
  legend.title = "SVI by 3-digit ZIP", # Title for the legend

COX PH model for risk of discontinuation

do a model selection

# Ensure the MASS package is installed
if (!requireNamespace("MASS", quietly = TRUE)) {
  install.packages("MASS")
}

library(survival)
library(MASS)
## 
## Attaching package: 'MASS'
## The following object is masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     select
# Define the initial full Cox model
cox_full_model <- coxph(Surv(time, status) ~ 
                          der_sex + SVI_3digit_class + group_BP + group_MHAndSU + age_at_episode + dayssup + pay_type + pat_region +
                          alcohol + nodrug + schizo + bipolar + anxiety + ptsd + 
                          hiv + depression + outpatient + psychiatric + telehealth +
                          mat + induction + bupre_tx + pdc_90, 
                        data = BTD_model_data)

# Perform stepwise selection using AIC
stepwise_model <- stepAIC(cox_full_model, direction = "both", trace = TRUE)

library(ggplot2)

# Extract data from the stepwise_model
# Replace stepwise_model with your actual model object
model_summary <- broom::tidy(stepwise_model, conf.int = TRUE)

# Inspect the summary to understand its structure
# print(model_summary)

# Create the forest_data dynamically without dplyr
forest_data <- model_summary

# Calculate Hazard Ratio (HR), Lower Confidence Interval (LowerCI), and Upper Confidence Interval (UpperCI)
forest_data$HR <- exp(forest_data$estimate)
forest_data$LowerCI <- exp(forest_data$conf.low)
forest_data$UpperCI <- exp(forest_data$conf.high)

# Assign Variable Groups using ifelse and grepl
forest_data$Group <- ifelse(grepl("Sex|Age|E|W|S|MW", forest_data$term), "Demographics",
                     ifelse(grepl("SVI", forest_data$term), "SVI by ZIP Code",
                     ifelse(grepl("Health Density", forest_data$term), "Mental Health Services Density",
                     ifelse(grepl("Provider Density", forest_data$term), "Provider Density",
                     ifelse(grepl("Psychiatric|Outpatient|Telehealth|Induction|Bupre_tx", forest_data$term), "Procedures",
                     ifelse(grepl("Alcohol|Drug|Mental|Schizo|Bipolar|PTSD|Depression|Anxiety|Hiv", forest_data$term), "Diagnostics",
                     ifelse(grepl("Medicaid|Medicare|Self-insured", forest_data$term), "Insurance Type", 
                            "Early Tx Adherence")))))))

# Select only the required columns
forest_data <- forest_data[, c("term", "HR", "LowerCI", "UpperCI", "Group")]

# Rename columns
colnames(forest_data) <- c("Variable", "HR", "LowerCI", "UpperCI", "Group")

# Sort by Group and Variable
forest_data <- forest_data[order(forest_data$Group, forest_data$Variable), ]

# Ensure the Variable column is a factor for ordering in the plot
forest_data$Variable <- factor(forest_data$Variable, levels = forest_data$Variable)
# Load required library

# Sort data by Group and Variable

# Create the forest plot
ggplot(forest_data, aes(x = HR, y = Variable, xmin = LowerCI, xmax = UpperCI, color = Group)) +
  geom_point(size = 3) +                           # Points for HR
  geom_errorbarh(height = 0.2) +                   # Horizontal error bars for CI
  scale_color_manual(values = c(
    "Demographics" = "red",
    "SVI by ZIP Code" = "blue",
    "Mental Health Services Density" = "orange",
    "Provider Density" = "green",
    "Diagnostics" = "brown",
    "Procedures" = "pink",
    "Other" = "purple",
    "Insurance Type" = "cyan"
  )) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 1, linetype = "dashed") +  # Reference line at HR=1
  labs(
    title = "Forest Plot for Cox Proportional Hazards Model",
    x = "Hazard Ratio (HR)",
    y = NULL,
    color = "Variable Group"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    legend.position = "right",                     # Legend on the right
    axis.text.y = element_text(size = 10),         # Adjust text size for y-axis labels
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)         # Center the title
  )
